Breast implants.

At one point in my life they seemed like a necessity.

Everyone I knew had them.

And according to society’s standards you couldn’t be “attractive” without them.

And I had them too.

At the time I thought they’d help with my insecurity.

They didn’t.

I thought they’d help me feel sexier, or more confident.

They didn’t.

As years went by the only thing they did was make me more unhealthy (breast implant illness is a real thing).

So I made the decision to remove mine.

To be natural.

I struggled with the decision but a funny thing happened when I took them out.

I felt sexier than I ever have.

Felt more confident than I ever have.

And I felt more empowered.

I also feel healthier than I’ve ever been. 

The lesson here? 

Fake things won’t help you find what you’re looking for.

Real beauty, or the feeling of being beautiful comes from within.

And it happens when you love yourself, finding pride in what your body is capable of instead of what it looks like. When you learn to appreciate your body inside and out, in your natural state.

Just the way you want to be.

How To: Find Rack Height For Back Squat 👇🏻

1️⃣ Stand up to the bar.
2️⃣ Aim for the bar to line up to mid chest.
3️⃣ check height by un-racking the bar and make sure it moves about 2-4 inches to clear the j-cup.

❌Do not have j-cup so high you have to tip toe the bar out of the cup.

❌Do not have j-cup so low you have to life the bar more than 4 inches to un-rack the weight.

Head Position PART 1

A forward head carry is getting more and more common with all the computer work and cellphone scrolling we do.

But it pops up in the gym too.

The biggest issue I see with head position, happens most often in the push-up and in the back squat.

Cues to keep your head in alignment with your body:
🔸Tuck chin back
🔸Align ear to shoulder
🔸 Pull base of the head into invisible wall

Things to avoid:
❌ Leading movement with chin
❌ Throwing top of the head back
❌ Looking down
❌ Looking at the ceiling

A great way to know if you need to focus on neck alignment:
😫If you experience neck tension after a workout
🎥Take a video and watch how you move!

Head Position PART 2

A forward head carry is getting more and more common with all the computer work and cellphone scrolling we do.

But it pops up in the gym too.

The biggest issue I see with head position, happens most often in the push-up and in the back squat.

Cues to keep your head in alignment with your body:
🔸Tuck chin back/looking up and out
🔸Align ear to shoulder
🔸 Pull base of the head into barbell

Things to avoid:
❌ Leading movement with chin
❌ Throwing top of the head back
❌ Looking all the way down at the floor
❌ Looking all the way up at the ceiling

A great way to know if you need to focus on neck alignment:
😫If you experience neck tension after a workout
🎥Take a video and watch how you move!

How do you add more weight to a workout?

So many of us train remotely.
We don’t see our coaches daily, they are out of state or we follow a program online.

When we are not in front of a coach it can be hard to know what weight to use, how to go up in weight, or when to go up in weight.

Here is an example of my own training session.
I was prescribed 8 reps of Hatfield Squats for 3 sets with Heavy resistance via doubled banded band tension.

I started with moderate band tension.
After 8 reps, it didn’t feel too difficult so I decided to lower the band attachment point. I thought maybe that would make it harder/hard enough.
But after 8 successful/moderately hard reps with the band attached lower, I felt I could still go heavier.
So I added another band.  The added band tension brought make it more challenging so I stayed there and proceeded to complete 3 sets.
I didn’t count the sets I did with the lighter weight/band tension.

My point is to encourage you to work up and challenge yourself!

It doesn’t matter if it’s bands, chains, weight, fancy bars or dumbbells. Don’t get caught up in that. 

Avoid setting self limitations.  Actually TEST yourself by adding weight.  You can always drop back down.

And DON’T cheat your sets.  Do your prescribed sets at the appropriate weight.

Discipline and motivation are related concepts, but they refer to different aspects of achieving goals or maintaining behaviors:
♦️Discipline:
 - Discipline is the ability to control one’s actions, thoughts, and behaviors to achieve a specific goal or maintain a certain standard.
 - It often involves consistency, self-control, and adherence to a set of rules or routines.
 - Discipline doesn’t necessarily rely on feeling motivated; it’s about doing what needs to be done even when you don’t feel like it.
 - It’s more focused on establishing habits and routines to maintain progress over the long term.

♦️Motivation:
 - Motivation is the inner or external drive that compels someone to take action or work towards a goal.
 - It can be influenced by emotions, desires, rewards, or external factors like encouragement from others.
 - Motivation can be fleeting and may come and go. It’s often linked to inspiration or enthusiasm.
 - People often seek ways to boost their motivation, such as setting inspiring goals or finding sources of inspiration.

In essence, discipline is about consistency and action, even in the absence of strong motivation, while motivation provides the initial spark or desire to pursue a goal. 

Both discipline and motivation are valuable for achieving success, as they complement each other. 
Discipline helps you stay on course when motivation wanes, and motivation can provide the energy and enthusiasm needed to start and sustain disciplined actions.

Not everything is “quick and easy”. The best part of achieving something is working for it.

Communicate.

In the quest for fitness greatness, there's a blunt truth you need to hear: Your coach isn't your babysitter. If you're serious about making progress, you've got to step up, speak out, and take complete ownership of your journey. It's time to cut the excuses and hold yourself accountable.
Here's the no-nonsense reality:

* No Hand-Holding: Your coach isn't a mind reader. They're here to guide and support, but they shouldn't have to drag information out of you. If you want results, be proactive!

* Your Progress, Your Duty: Want to see change? Your coach needs to know what's happening in your fitness world.

* Own Your Actions: Accountability isn't your coach's job; it's yours. If you're not seeing results, don't point fingers. Look in the mirror and ask, "Am I giving it my all?"

* Results Require Feedback: Effective communication forms the backbone of results. If you're not telling your coach how you feel, what hurts, or what you love, they can't help.

* Adapt or Stagnate: Life throws curveballs. When it does, speak up!

Now, how do you get in the driver's seat of your fitness journey?

* Regularly Report In: Don't make your coach hunt you down for updates. Keep them in the loop with regular updates via any means necessary.

* Demand Answers: Have questions? Ask them. Your coach is your fitness guru, so don't be afraid to seek wisdom.

* Truth Trumps All: Honesty is non-negotiable. Your coach needs to hear it all—wins, losses, and everything in between. Only then can they provide real help.

* Set the Bar High: Collaborate with your coach to set challenging, laser-focused goals. These goals will propel your training forward.

* Embrace Feedback: Be open to criticism and suggestions. It's how you grow.

The bottom line? Your coach is your partner, not your crutch. By stepping up, taking charge, and being brutally honest with yourself and your coach, you you seize control of your fitness.

What’s the white stuff?

Two simple rules:
Chalk your hands.
Baby powder your thighs.
DO NOT MIX THEM!

I’ve seen a lot of new lifters put chalk on their thighs because they see lifters with white powder on their legs. But it’s important to know that:
White stuff ON LEGS = BABY POWDER
White stuff ON HANDS = CHALK

The goal is to have a tight strong grip and to have the bar slide up the thighs.  Chalk on the hands helps the hands grip the bar. Powder on the thighs helps the bar slide.

Chalk- grip
Baby powder- slide

This plank requires you to activate every muscle in your body!  It is common to get into a plank and stack your bones and just chill until time is up. But not with this one!

🔻Make two fists and dig them into the ground.

🔻Push your toes into the ground.

🔻Engage your hips by dropping them down into alignment with your shoulders.

🔻Push your belly button toward the ceiling engaging the abs.

🔻Drive the back of the head toward the ceiling keeping your eyes on your thumbs.

🔻Now squeeze every muscle! Turn on the traps, lats, erectors, abs, glutes, quads, calves, toes, hamstrings, biceps, triceps, etc…

🔻Continue to scan up and down your body to ensure everything is flexed!

Throwback to setting a World Record 5 months pregnant 🤰
⁣
When it comes to women’s health, there are so many gaps in the research.⁣
⁣
Most research studies are done on and with men and that information is then applied to women.⁣
⁣
Women are NOT mini men.⁣
⁣
We have different hormone profiles, different distributions of muscle fiber types, injury risks and need to be treated differently in many scenarios.⁣
⁣
⁣
There is very limited research on women and women’s health.⁣
⁣
ESPECIALLY pregnant women.⁣
⁣
⁣
Women are difficult to study…👇🏻
⁣
⁣
Here are a few questions to keep in mind while reading a study:⁣
⁣
·Are there additional studies that show the same thing?⁣
⁣
·Is the population a niche group?⁣
⁣
·Are there studies that directly refute the current one?⁣
⁣
·Do their claims make sense physiologically?⁣
⁣
·What specifically were the methods used in conducting the study?⁣
⁣
·Who made up the group of subjects?⁣
⁣
·What were the age and training status of participants?⁣
⁣
When conducting research on women participants, consistent bloodwork is needed to track⁣ hormones.  Other factors need to be taken into account like, menopause, birth control, pregnancy, breastfeeding, athletic background (or lack of), the list goes on…
⁣
There are little to no studies/information for pregnant women or pregnant athletes.  If we look at why, it is because it is not ethical to study.⁣
⁣
So, what are we supposed to do?⁣
⁣
“Listen to your body” is the most common advice.⁣
⁣
Here is what I did…⁣
I trained while pregnant.⁣
⁣
I deadlifted 350 lbs.⁣
⁣
Was my pregnancy healthy? ⁣
⁣
Yup.⁣
⁣
Was and is my baby healthy?⁣
⁣
Yup.⁣
⁣
Does that mean you should do what I did?⁣
⁣
Nope.⁣
⁣
All bodies tell different stories.⁣
⁣
But one thing I do know, is that women need to be studied. And as women, we need to be educated in reading research studies to make sure women are represented or the information is applicable to where our bodies are physiologically.⁣
⁣
⁣

Should you train when you are sick?

What kind of sicknesss is it?

A head cold with symptoms like: stuffy or runny nose, congestion and sore throat is normally something you can train through.
You want to avoid public gyms because you don’t want to spread the virus, but a bit of movement or light workout is probably ok.

Stomach flu with symptoms like: nausea, vomiting and diarrhea is something that normally comes on fast and also goes away fast. But training through it is not a great idea. The advantage of Strength Training Building Up, Not Beating Down

When it comes to body transformations, there is debate between strength training and cardio. While cardio has its benefit (and it does), let’s discuss why strength training is superior.

*Metabolic Benefit*
Strength training builds lean muscle mass. More muscle translates to a higher resting metabolic rate, ensuring you burn calories even at rest. Unlike cardio, which primarily burns calories during the activity, the metabolic impact of strength training extends far beyond the gym.

*Body Composition Transformation*
Cardio may shed pounds, but it often involves muscle loss. Strength training, on the other hand, actively contributes to body composition transformation by adding muscle mass. This enhances aesthetics 💪🏻 

*Post-Workout Calorie Burn*
The “afterburn” effect, scientifically known as excess post-exercise oxygen consumption (EPOC), is higher with strength training. Intense lifting sessions can elevate your metabolism for hours after the workout, promoting continuous calorie burn and fat loss.

*Joint Health and Longevity*
Hours of repetitive cardio can take a toll on joints. Strength training, when done with proper form, strengthens muscles around joints, potentially reducing the risk of injuries and supporting long-term joint health.

*Hormonal Impact*
Strength training triggers the release of hormones which are essential for muscle growth and fat metabolism. This hormonal response contributes significantly to the body’s ability to transform and adapt positively (hello abs!)

Cardio has its place in promoting cardiovascular health. Strength training promotes muscle growth, it builds you up, shaping a stronger, leaner physique, without the wear and tear associated with excessive cardio. 
Consider incorporating a balanced blend of both, but let the weights take the lead to a transformed body.
